  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Financial institutions must:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. Typical requirements:\n- Customer due diligence\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting large or suspicious transactions\n- Screening against sanctions lists\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations apply to banks, credit unions, investment firms, cryptocurrency exchanges, and other financial service providers.",
